column2: OH-OCCHA";"3660 SHIRLEY ROAD";"YOUNGSTOWN";"OH";44502;"MAHONING";"330-476-5829";"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"mycapyoungstown@gmail.com";"The Mahoning Youngstown Community Action Partnership (MYCAP) was founded in 1965. We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.

column1: Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People

column2: OH MCCTC";"7300 NORTH PALMYRA RD";"CANFIELD";"OH";44406;"MAHONING";"330-729-4011";"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"mycapyoungstown@gmail.com";"The Mahoning Youngstown Community Action Partnership (MYCAP) was founded in 1965. We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.

column1: Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People

column2: We Care...

column1: The needs of children and their parents are the primary concerns of Youthland Academy's child care philosophy. By providing the best possible daycare to children
column2: we are contributing to the happiness and the security of their parents and to the community they live in.

column1: First and foremost
column2: Youthland Academy provides children constant and alert supervision in a safe environment
column3: screened from hazards. The large classroom with designated area for learning centers provide for both quiet and active play. Our entire program is designed to enable children to have a positive self-concept and to know success and fulfillment through programs of positive self-concept and to know success from the beginning. This is possible because our Academy environment provides children the opportunity to be safe in their quest as natural leaders.

column1: Youthland Academy isn't merely a childcare center
column2: it's a ""learning center"" that assists children to realize success and fulfillment through programs of positive self-image. Children experience the joy of learning; they feel loved and accepted. Our program is our attitude.

column1: Our Teachers and Directors are provided monthly themes that ignite each child's unique pleasure in learning. The monthly curriculum suggests proven ways to include these themes in a variety of ""discovery centered"" activities. Using the curriculum's themes
column2: each teacher designs individualized lesson plans. We do not adhere to the standardized lesson plan because we feel there is no standard child or standard class. This is why we keep our teacher-child ratio at the level that comfortably supports personal attention.

column1: Included with classroom discovery and stimulation are field trips. At some of our Academies
column2: we also provide activities such as gymnastics and dance classes. These services enable parents to further enrich their children's lives without cutting into the quality time parents and children share after working hours.

column1: Progress reports are given to parents to keep them up-to-date on the total growth of their children. Formal conferences are scheduled yearly to discuss a child's progress. However
column2: parents are encouraged to meet their child's teacher and director
column3: and visit the Academy at any time they feel necessary.";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/locations/west-carrollton-school-age";;"6:30am-2:00pm";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/careers";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/attachments/14/enrollment1.pdf";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/attachments/124/ParentHandbook2k14.pdf";"y";"y";"y";"y";"y";"y";;"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/138/content_1377348_10151877935546211_176283268_n.jpg";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/2/content_tod-cincinnati-day-care.jpg";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/141/content_426470_10151492431831211_1832794487_n.jpg";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/139/content_580490_10151499682281211_1585200262_n.jpg";;

821751;"AGAPE CHILDREN'S CENTER";"1060 SMILEY AVE";"CINCINNATI";"OH";45240;"HAMILTON";5136742323;"http://agapechildrenscenter.org/";"tpayne@dayspringcincy.org";"Ten Reasons To Choose Agape!
1) We are a non-profit ministry- this means that the revenue generated by our program is invested into the lives of your children! We are here to make a difference in the lives of our families!
2) Our integrity- we believe in striving for excellence. We have a history of nearly flawless state licensing inspections because we endeavor to represent Christ in all that we do.
3) We have a low staff turnover because we make careful selections in the hiring of our all Christian staff. Staff are encouraged to maintain their relationship with God and their roles as parents
column2: spouses
column3: children and friends in God's order of priority. We have several in-house teacher-aides that serve as substitutes at times- they are familiar with our children
column4: our class routines and provide love and care for children in the absence of the lead teacher in each room.

column1: 4) Our experience- Our fourteen most senior employees have been here an average of over seven years. We LOVE what we do! Our newest staff members are selected because they FIRST have a love for children. Then education and experiences are considered in the selection and training processes.

5) Our training- training is provided and paid for staff. Ongoing support in childhood development and classroom management is provided as staff mature. Staff are encouraged through tuition reimbursement to continue their professional growth. Many staff are degreed or have their Child Development Associates Degree (CDA) through the Council for Professional Recognition
column2: Washington
column3: DC. We have an on-staff advisor to make this process convenient for our staff. Through STEP UP TO QUALITY
column4: our staff have access to scholarships that cover 90% of their college expenses!

column1: 6) Our facility
column2: including the full-sized gym
column3: allows us plenty of space for exploring and experiencing fun ways to learn with our friends.

column1: 7) Our congregation supports Agape as an outreach ministry- we are not viewed as a ""profit machine"" to generate church income
column2: but as part of the ministry of Dayspring.

column1: 8) We are privileged to be able to combine our call to ministry with our chosen vocation. Many people minister to children- we do it all week long!

9) Equipment purchases and supplies are a priority even though we do not charge as much as many other centers do. We want to meet the needs that staff have for classroom supplies and program materials.

10) Our literacy based program provides many opportunities for child interaction with books- our teachers receive collections of library books monthly that change as our weekly themes change. This provides a rich and ever-changing resource for learning. Our K4 and preschool classes use a phonics-based reading curriculum that prepares them for a successful Kindergarten year. 821810;"ALTON HALL AFTERSCHOOL PROGRAM";"1000 ALTON RD";"GALLOWAY";"OH";43119;"FRANKLIN";6148787260;"http://ahes.swcsd.us/";"tim.barton@swcsd.us";"Welcome to our new Web site! We have created a new site to help provide our parents and community members with more current and up-to-date information regarding our school. Please be patient with us as we add more and more information to our site!
Alton Hall Elementary School services the needs of more than 500 learners in Kindergarten through 4th Grade.

Alton Hall is a school that provides high expectations for learners by personalizing and individualizing instruction. LIBERTY ST";"ASHLAND";"OH";44805;"ASHLAND";4192818001;"http://www.knohoco.org/index.php/services/youth-services/head-start";;"Kno Ho Co Ashland CAC operates a federal Head Start site at 5 locations in the service area. Head Start is a federally funded preschool specifically for low income children ages 3 to 5.
Head Start is a national program that promotes school readiness by enhancing the social and cognitive development of children through the provision of educational
column2: health
column3: nutritional
column4: social and other services to enrolled children and families.

column1: Head Start programs are operated by local organizations
column2: usually nonprofits
column3: but not always. Children who attend Head Start participate in a variety of educational activities. They also receive free medical and dental care
column4: enjoy healthy meals and snacks
column5: and play outdoors and indoors in a safe setting. Head Start centers are required to meet all State and local licensing regulations.

column1: Head Start provides children with activities that help them grow mentally
column2: socially
column3: emotionally and physically while assisting them with school readiness.

column1: The majority of the children served in Head Start are low income
column2: below 130% of the national poverty guidelines. About ten percent of the children served may be above income and are selected based on need.

column1: Kno Ho Co Ashland CAC currently operates half day Head Start programs at all 5 locations. Children attend for 3.5 hours per day
column2: for 128 days during a school year. Classes typically begin in September and last until mid-May. Classes are held Monday through Thursday with Fridays available to staff for training.

column1: Head Start teachers must have a degree in Early Childhood Education or a related field. Many of the teachers hold State of Ohio Teaching licenses. Assistant teachers must have a minimum of a CDA certificate
column2: but many have taken college level classes in Early Childhood Education.

column1: Kno Ho Co Ashland CAC Head Start centers participate in the State of Ohio’s Step Up to Quality rating system. All centers have been rated as 4 stars.
Ashland County Head Start centers are located in the villages of Sullivan and Loudonville in Ashland County and in the City of Ashland.
In Holmes County centers are located in the villages of Glenmont and Millersburg.
Children with disabilities are welcome in the Head Start program and may receive special services or therapies.
Some Head Start centers provide transportation by Licensed Ohio School Bus.";"http://www.knohoco.org/index.php/services/youth-services/head-start";;;;;;"n";"n";"y";"y";"n";"n";;;;;;;

821966;"BELPRE HEAD START";"2014 ROCKLAND AVENUE";"BELPRE";"OH";45714;"WASHINGTON";7404237120;"http://www.wmcap.org/headstart.html";;"Head Start is a free preschool for eligible families that specializes in the educational and social development of young children age 3-5. Our number one goal is to prepare children for kindergarten. Our curriculum takes into account the importance of social skills and group-work while focusing on the necessary educational skills.
Head Start is available in either one of our centers or in your own home.

The Head Start Home Base option focuses on parents as educators and includes regular home visits by an assigned home visitor who works with families and supports parents in meeting the needs of their young children. Home Base is available anywhere in Washington or Morgan Counties. Our centers offer 3-½ hour classes four days a week and provide transportation where available
column2: breakfast or lunch and a snack. Both of our options provide services for children with disabilities
column3: family nights
column4: parent groups and more.

column1: Head Start teachers are constantly receiving the most current training in childhood education and development. We also work closely with the local school systems on many issues and have an on-going evaluation process that allows the teachers and parents to monitor the child's progress.

Program goals are set for improving the school readiness of children that align with the requirements and expectations of the schools. School readiness goals are the expectations that children's evolvement of language and literacy
column2: cognition and general knowledge
column3: approaches towards learning
column4: physical well-being and motor development
column5: and social and emotional development will improve children's' readiness for kindergarten.";"http://www.wmcap.org/headstart.html";;;"http://www.wmcap.org/employment.html";"http://www.wmcap.org/app_headstart.pdf";;"y";"y";"y";"y";"n";"n";"http://www.wmcap.org/_gfxredesign/topbar_left.gif";"http://www.wmcap.org/gfx-photos/service_headstart.jpg";;;;;

Preschool education must offer a fine balance between ""structure"" and ""freedom of choice"". The child will be allowed to reach out to fulfill their natural curiosities and to explore the obvious. Our well educated staff will guide the child and direct them to grow by enhancing their experiences. BLC staff will offer the balance a child needs to feel secure and stable while attending our center. It is a known fact that all children will learn and progress at their own rate. Children
column3: however
column4: progress more rapidly if provided with the right stimulation and environment. Our center strives to offer the child a comfortable and secure environment that will stimulate and challenge the child to reach their full potential. We encourage children to make choices and to participate in group activities. We believe at Blanchester Learning Center
column5: that early preschool years are very important for children to develop a strong self-image. We provide age appropriate opportunities for growth in self-direction and independence. We encourage self-expression
column6: creativity
column9: we want the children to feel safe and have fun learning. It is our goal for each and every child to look forward to attending our center. We also believe that the parents must feel confident and assured that their child will be cared for in an appropriate
column10: nurturing and loving way. We encourage parents to get to know the staff and develop a strong partnership of Shared Care Giving with them. Thank you for sharing your child with us.";"https://www.facebook.com/BlanLearningCenter/info?tab=page_info";;"Mon - Fri:

column1: To reduce poverty and promote self-sufficiency.
The Broad Objectives of the Agency are:
· To provide quality services to low-income individuals and families.
· To advocate for a poverty-free community.
· To assist families to become self-reliant.
· To stimulate expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development-related activities.

We have been bring quality programs to the Grand Valley area since 2004. Choice Child Care is licensed by the state of Ohio to care for infants through school-aged children.  Before and after-school care is available with local school busing. The center also offers preschool and Pre-Kindergarten classes for children three through five years of age. Give us a call at (440) 437-7770 and we will be glad to answer your questions and/or arrange a tour of the center.

The large 5800 sq. ft. building was designed specifically for the care and teaching of young children. Each classroom is spacious and divided into clear individual learning centers holding a wide variety of materials. Every classroom has its own kitchenette area and is equipped with restrooms scaled to the size for the age group. The building is also equipped with an emergency monitoring system that is wired for fire and other emergency services. Exits are available out of every classroom directly to the large three acre playground. The outside environment has wide open areas of grass for ball play
column2: mulch for climbing
column3: and a pavilion for sun shelter.

column1: Your child’s safety is a primary concern and as a result we have equipped the building with a video monitoring system including a front entry-video camera.  Each classroom has a monitor displaying the front entrance and staff can release the locking mechanism from any classroom to allow authorized individuals to enter.

The professional teaching staff has a wealth of experience. We emphasize the importance of quality care and are adamant about having low adult-to-child ratios and maintaining small group sizes. All programing is developmentally appropriate and focuses on the Early Learning Content Standards.
We had an abundant of exciting activities through out the year that enhance our programs and tie in community involvement. To name a few of our annual visitors are Jungle Terry
column2: the local fire department
column3: paramedics. dental hygienists
column4: and farmers. We recently purchased an activity bus making it possible for our school age group to travel to places such as Deer Park

column3: and effective method of education that was created by Dr. Maria Montessori
column4: the first woman physician to graduate from the University of Rome. On the basis of her scientific observations of behavior of young children
column5: she found that children learn best in a homelike setting filled with developmentally appropriate materials that support each child's unique growth and learning abilities.

column1: Key facts that differentiate the Montessori from the conventional approach are: focus on ""total development"" of child
column2: the environment
column3: appropriate materials
column4: and the prepared teacher.

column1: The Montessori environment cultivates children's natural desire to learn at their own pace without interruption or coercion. The children learn new skills through a free choice of hands-on activities
column2: with guidance from a prepared teacher who observes
column3: counsels
column4: and demonstrates appropriate activities to individuals or small groups. Montessori materials are age-appropriate
column5: concrete
column6: self teaching
column7: and open-ended; they reflect reality and require active participation.

column1: The result is a child with a well-rounded personality
column2: positive self-image
column3: improved physical coordination
column4: better self-care
column5: and an accurate perception of the world.

column2: that early childhood years should be a time when children learn and play in a loving
column3: nurturing Christian environment and having fun exploring and discovering new ideas and concepts. Children are creative and receptive
column4: our program strives to nurture and encourage these qualities in our students.

column1: Through the experiences your child encounters your child will become more aware of the world around them and stir up curiosity so they will become eager to learn.  During the early years of your child’s life there is rapid growth taking place and important habits and attitudes are being formed.  These concepts attitudes and habits will affect your child’s personality and his/her potential to cope successfully in any environment.
The goal of First Class Christian Child Care and Preschool is to provide an atmosphere that encourages your child’s intellectual
column2: spiritual
column3: emotional
column4: social and physical growth and development as a whole.  We want these first experiences with others to be successful beginnings to the many years of formal education ahead.  Through the programs at our center your child will develop self-discipline
column5: cooperative work and play
column6: creative self-expression
column8: development of coordination and muscle control
column9: as well as many other social and physical growths.

column1: Our curriculum includes sharing and conversation time
column2: reading books
column3: singing songs
column4: finger-plays
column5: creative art activities
column6: crafts
column7: and games.  Children have the opportunity to learn concepts like; shapes
column10: and the celebration of birthdays and holidays. Our center is designed to reflect knowledge of child growth and development
column11: offering learning opportunities that are age appropriate and individual appropriate.  Children will then naturally move to their next level of development.

column1: Communication with your child’s next teacher will assist our planning to prepare your child to succeed to the next level or school grade.  Our teaching methods and materials encourage independence
column2: discovery and experimentation.  Materials are easily accessible to all students.  Materials are carefully chosen to serve as learning tools for younger children.  Our programs are stimulus-rich environments with a wide variety of learning materials.

column1: We are responding to today's working parents'/guardians' growing needs for the type of excellent child care and learning facility. We strive to instill in children a life long passion for learning by allowing them time for exploration

column1: We take children ages 6 weeks to 12 years. We have have five different age groups. Our first age group is Infants age ranging from 6 weeks to 18 months. column1: Our school follows the Ohio Academic Content Standards for Preschool.  These set guidelines list what materials and subject matters must be covered during the preschool year.  This material is used as a learning step
column2: and the Kindergarten teacher will take this preschool knowledge and build from it.

column1: We are also a one star rated Step Up To Quality program. Step Up To Quality is Ohio's voluntary quality rating system for child care programs recognizing early care and education programs that exceed quality for Ohio's children.
We have two classrooms that separate the 3-4 year old from the 4-5 year old preschoolers.  This allows you to send your child multiple years if you chose
column2: without them repeating the same program.

Our lunches our catered in and contain all four major food groups. We serve milk with breakfast and lunch
column2: daily. We serve our children portions that are guided by the U.S.D.A. Standards. We keep our sweets to a minimum. You are welcome to bring in a treat for your child’s birthday to share with the class. We pride ourselves on our staff guiding our children through their daily activities using developmentally appropriate practices. We match each child’s goals with their individual developmental level in each and every area of learning. We encourage our children to explore many avenues of creativity. Painting alone offers so many creative choices. Here are a few examples. Painting with…marbles
column3: fruit
column4: fingers
column5: feet
column6: water and sponges are just a few of the many sensory materials that we offer for our children to create their masterpieces. We also incorporate many unconventional art materials. While out on our nature walks
column7: we gather all sorts of materials for our art projects. They include
column11: twigs and seeds. Children enjoy creating nature collages. Our children’s art projects are their own
column13: when their turtle has three eyes and eight feet
column14: you will know this is straight from their imagination! We offer many opportunities throughout the day for our children to enjoy and learn through literature. Each of our classrooms have a book nook for our children to “chill out” and relax with a book. We also offer literacy teaching through word recognition by having your child’s name on their lunch table and cubicle as well as items labeled throughout the classroom
column15: using Spanish as well as English. We do encourage our school-agers to work on their homework with the assistance of the teacher

column2: the YMCA has been known for its commitment to family life. YMCA programs and services have grown and adapted to the changing needs of families. Today

column4: yet affordable childcare they can depend on. Whether your child is attending our infant/toddler program
column5: preschool or our school age child care program
column6: our goal is to provide a safe
column7: fun environment. Like all Y programs

column1: With so many demands on today’s families
column2: parents need all the support they can get. That’s why child care at the Y is about more than looking after kids. It’s about nurturing their development by providing a safe place for them to learn the foundational skills of Early Childhood Education
column3: develop healthy
column4: trusting relationships
column5: and build self-reliance through the Y values. We believe the values and skills learned early on are vital building blocks for quality of life. The Preschool program is focused from the very beginning on Kindergarten readiness. We begin our Early Preschool program with our 2 ½ year olds. Our year-round curriculum includes thematic units that move the children through a progression of learning that can be adapted to meet the individual needs of the children at each level. Our facility allows us to provide the children breakfast
column6: a full hot lunch and an afternoon snack as well as weekly swimming lessons and weekly gymnastics classes. We strive to educate the parent about the importance of their role in their child’s education from the very beginning. We keep parents informed through newsletters
column8: formal assessments and an open door policy that allows parents full view of what their child is involved in daily. We also encourage the parents to participate in family events throughout the year and to utilize our facility. A strong family relationship is vital to the ongoing education of our children
column9: and we know that strong kids and strong families build strong communities.

column1: We emphasize the four core values: caring
column2: honesty
column3: respect
column4: and responsibility. We teach this to the children through day to day experiences
column5: activities
column6: and lessons. We give the children the opportunity to use verbal communication to solve problems. Our staff serves as positive role models and provides care that is supportive
column8: warm and responsive to each child's needs.  Our open door policy allows parents the freedom of knowing what their children are doing at all times during the day.

The owners Renee Miller and Elizabeth Kelkenberg have known each other for over 20 years. column1: 824129;"MCCARTNEY HEAD START LEARNING CENTER";"1988 MCCARTNEY ROAD";"YOUNGSTOWN";"OH";44505;"MAHONING";3307477921;"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"mycapyoungstown@gmail.com";"The Mahoning Youngstown Community Action Partnership (MYCAP) was founded in 1965. We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.
Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People

column1: 824190;"MILLBROOK NURSERY SCHOOL AND KINDERGARTEN";"1405 MOLER RD";"COLUMBUS";"OH";43207;"FRANKLIN";6144430503;"http://www.millbrooknurseryschoolandkindergarten.org/";"﻿sware36714@aol.com";"Millbrook Nursery School & Kindergarten is Fun
column2: Friendly and Family Oriented!!

column1: Explore an academic preschool that has been guiding children since 1962! Our goal is to give your child a solid educational foundation that will create successful experiences in school and fostors a lifetime of learning. Our unique program is designed to fit each child's individual educational needs and encorporate social skills in a classroom setting. We have seperate classrooms for each age group to provide a structured learning environment.
For five decades
column2: Millbrook has provided families with a safe
column3: fun and clean facility. Our teachers are degreed
column4: experienced and attentive working with not only the children but the parents as well. We have a Parent Participation Program which allows parents the opportunity to stay involved with their child academic success each step of the way.

column1: Millbrook offers home cooked healthy meals and snacks that aid in educating not only the mind but the body as well. Our program goes above and beyond to give each child a balance diet and plenty of exercise. We are committed to giving each child as many positive experiences possible for their mind and body for years to come.
We offer full-time
column2: part-time preschool programs
column3: latchkey and transportation for school-age children to and from school. Private pay and subsidized childcare is available. Our program is Step Up to Quality award winners
column4: as well has a Healthy Habits/Healthy Weights participants. We are also proud to announce we are partnered with Mayor Coleman's Early Start Columbus Program.

824193;"MILLERSBURG HEAD START";"224 NORTH CLAY STREET";"MILLERSBURG";"OH";44654;"HOLMES";3306749100;"http://www.knohoco.org/index.php/services/youth-services/head-start";;"Kno Ho Co Ashland CAC operates a federal Head Start site at 5 locations in the service area. Head Start is a federally funded preschool specifically for low income children ages 3 to 5.
Head Start is a national program that promotes school readiness by enhancing the social and cognitive development of children through the provision of educational
column2: health
column3: nutritional
column4: social and other services to enrolled children and families.

column1: Head Start programs are operated by local organizations
column2: usually nonprofits
column3: but not always. Children who attend Head Start participate in a variety of educational activities. They also receive free medical and dental care
column4: enjoy healthy meals and snacks
column5: and play outdoors and indoors in a safe setting. Head Start centers are required to meet all State and local licensing regulations.

column1: Head Start provides children with activities that help them grow mentally
column2: socially
column3: emotionally and physically while assisting them with school readiness.

column1: The majority of the children served in Head Start are low income
column2: below 130% of the national poverty guidelines. About ten percent of the children served may be above income and are selected based on need.

column1: Kno Ho Co Ashland CAC currently operates half day Head Start programs at all 5 locations. Children attend for 3.5 hours per day
column2: for 128 days during a school year. Classes typically begin in September and last until mid-May. Classes are held Monday through Thursday with Fridays available to staff for training.

column1: Head Start teachers must have a degree in Early Childhood Education or a related field. Many of the teachers hold State of Ohio Teaching licenses. Assistant teachers must have a minimum of a CDA certificate
column2: but many have taken college level classes in Early Childhood Education.

column1: Kno Ho Co Ashland CAC Head Start centers participate in the State of Ohio’s Step Up to Quality rating system. All centers have been rated as 4 stars.
Ashland County Head Start centers are located in the villages of Sullivan and Loudonville in Ashland County and in the City of Ashland.
In Holmes County centers are located in the villages of Glenmont and Millersburg.
Children with disabilities are welcome in the Head Start program and may receive special services or therapies.
Some Head Start centers provide transportation by Licensed Ohio School Bus.";"http://www.knohoco.org/index.php/services/youth-services/head-start";;;;;;"n";"n";"y";"y";"n";"n";;;;;;;

column1: 824453;"OCCHA HEAD START LEARNING CENTER";"3660 SHIRLEY ROAD";"YOUNGSTOWN";"OH";44502;"MAHONING";3307477921;"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"mycapyoungstown@gmail.com";"The Mahoning Youngstown Community Action Partnership (MYCAP) was founded in 1965. We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.
Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People
column2: Changing Lives.";"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"https://www.facebook.com/pages/MYCAP-Mahoning-Youngstown-Community-Action-Partnership/253808185491";;"http://www.my-cap.org/about/employment";;;"n";"n";"y";"y";"n";"n";"http://www.my-cap.org/wp-content/themes/mycap/images/mycaplogo.png";;;;;;

We strive to provide an environment where children feel safe and are encouraged to be active and creative explorers trying out their own ideas and thinking their own thoughts in areas that interest them. column1: 824535;"PARMA PRESCHOOL INC";"5280 BROADVIEW RD";"PARMA";"OH";44134;"CUYAHOGA";4402380193;"http://www.parmapreschool.org/home/";"KimSurniak@parmapreschool.org  ";"Imagine a school...
where children create the curriculum

column1: where nature is valued
where children are seen as capable of learning on their own
where families are valued
where children learn through THEIR learning style (hands on
column2: visual

column1: Not all babies start babbling words and sounds at the same time or learn to crawl at the exact same age.  Children grow and develop at their own
column2: individual pace.  This continues throughout childhood and is respected at Parma Preschool.

column1: When some children start preschool they know the whole alphabet and can write their name.  Others cannot even hold a pencil.  Why then
column2: would we assume that all children need to be taught the letter A at the same point in the school year?

column1: We don't teach like that.
Preschool is much more than ABCs and 123s... it's learning to get along with peers
column2: share
column3: be kind and repectful to others.  It is learning to be healthy and active.  It is learning how to problem solve
column4: negotiate
column5: figure things out and make choices; not just being told what to do
column6: how to do it and when!

column1: We follow the children's lead
column2: meet them where they are at and help them reach the next level in their development. column2: it can be extremely more difficult. Many parents unfortunately know what it feels like to have their child not accepted into a child care program because of medical needs
column3: behavioral challenges
column4: or simply not being toilet trained. The Robin Rogers Day Service is a state licensed day care program
column5: whose mission is to serve children with developmental delays and disabilities. Our program has existed for over thirty years
column6: with a rich and successful history of serving children with disabilities. Our staff boasts an average of a dozen years of experience each. They receive annual training in CPR and First Aid
column9: as well as regular training on medical issues
column11: and a wide variety of other areas imperative to teaching young children. We contract for services through both the Allen County Department of Job & Family Services and the Allen County Childrens Services Board. In addition to serving children with special needs

824866;"SEBRING HEAD START LEARNING CENTER";"126 W INDIANA AVE";"SEBRING";"OH";44672;"MAHONING";3309382926;"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"mycapyoungstown@gmail.com";"The Mahoning Youngstown Community Action Partnership (MYCAP) was founded in 1965. We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.
Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People
column2: Changing Lives.";"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"https://www.facebook.com/pages/MYCAP-Mahoning-Youngstown-Community-Action-Partnership/253808185491";;"http://www.my-cap.org/about/employment";;;"n";"n";"y";"y";"n";"n";"http://www.my-cap.org/wp-content/themes/mycap/images/mycaplogo.png";;;;;;

We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.
Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People

column1: Children's Place is open from 7 a.m. until 6 p.m. year round. We serve children from 18 months old through the fourth grade of elementary school. We take the security of our students seriously. The classroom doors are locked during class-time
column2: and we have installed a new keypad system on the entry doors to help ensure the safety of everyone.

column1: Our student teacher ratio is kept low to help give each child the quality care they deserve. Our four year old preschool class has a teacher to student ratio of 1 to 12. Our school age program has a teacher to student ratio of 1 to 15.

825575;"WASHINGTON COUNTY LEARNING CENTER - EWING";"1701 COLEGATE DRIVE";"MARIETTA";"OH";45750;"WASHINGTON";7403736016;"http://www.wmcap.org/headstart.html";;"Head Start is a free preschool for eligible families that specializes in the educational and social development of young children age 3-5. Our number one goal is to prepare children for kindergarten. Our curriculum takes into account the importance of social skills and group-work while focusing on the necessary educational skills.
Head Start is available in either one of our centers or in your own home.

The Head Start Home Base option focuses on parents as educators and includes regular home visits by an assigned home visitor who works with families and supports parents in meeting the needs of their young children. Home Base is available anywhere in Washington or Morgan Counties. Our centers offer 3-½ hour classes four days a week and provide transportation where available
column2: breakfast or lunch and a snack. Both of our options provide services for children with disabilities
column3: family nights
column4: parent groups and more.

column1: Head Start teachers are constantly receiving the most current training in childhood education and development. We also work closely with the local school systems on many issues and have an on-going evaluation process that allows the teachers and parents to monitor the child's progress.

Program goals are set for improving the school readiness of children that align with the requirements and expectations of the schools. School readiness goals are the expectations that children's evolvement of language and literacy
column2: cognition and general knowledge
column3: approaches towards learning
column4: physical well-being and motor development
column5: and social and emotional development will improve children's' readiness for kindergarten.";"http://www.wmcap.org/headstart.html";;;"http://www.wmcap.org/employment.html";"http://www.wmcap.org/app_headstart.pdf";;"y";"y";"y";"y";"n";"n";"http://www.wmcap.org/_gfxredesign/topbar_left.gif";"http://www.wmcap.org/gfx-photos/service_headstart.jpg";;;;;

column1: Mrs. Sarah Benson worked as a Program Director for Mrs. DeHaven in Head Start. She and her husband
column2: Robert bought the Center in 1969 and moved into the second floor

column4: Eric and Tony
column5: until the Center expanded into the area in 1984.

column1: Mrs. DeHaven had dreams of what she wanted WeeHaven to be. Many of her ideas have been realized over the years. including 3 expansions. Today what you see at WeeHaven is a result of the 27 years of the Labor of Love and dedication to children by the Benson’s and Mrs. DeHaven.
In January of 1996

column3: Sue and Greg were parents of two children who had attended WeeHaven for 5 years. It was their objective to Keep the WeeHaven tradition going by continuing to provide a Center with a warm
column4: loving

column1: 825637;"CDI HEAD START-WESTCHESTER";"122 WESTCHESTER DRIVE";"YOUNGSTOWN";"OH";44515;"MAHONING";"330-476-5830";"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"mycapyoungstown@gmail.com";"The Mahoning Youngstown Community Action Partnership (MYCAP) was founded in 1965. We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.
Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People
column2: Changing Lives.";"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"https://www.facebook.com/pages/MYCAP-Mahoning-Youngstown-Community-Action-Partnership/253808185491";;"http://www.my-cap.org/about/employment";;;"n";"n";"y";"y";"n";"n";"http://www.my-cap.org/wp-content/themes/mycap/images/mycaplogo.png";;;;;;

column2: hands-on experiences occurring during play. Our approach to Early Childhood Education is that the teachers builds upon
column3: not directs or controls
column4: the thoughts and actions of the children. Child-initiated activities foster independence at a time when it is important for pre-schoolers to begin to develop self-reliance. We resist the increasing pressure to teach young children facts and figures before they are ready and to focus instead on nurturing their special skills and abilities. Children actively playing are busy learning about the world in ways children learn best by exploring and working with people
column5: materials and ideas. Children are much more likely to learn when they become intensely involved in projects of their own design. Our teacher’s role is to ensure that the children choose and organize their own work by helping each child develop a plan
column6: define a sequence of steps
column7: and identify needed materials. Significant amount of time are spent in child/adult interaction. Talking together
column8: sharing ideas and playing together are essential parts of our program

column1: Ample space is important for active learning and the arrangement of our classrooms reflect the belief that children learn best in a stimulating
column2: but ordered environment. The classroom is divided into well-defined work areas
column3: and the materials in each area are organized to enable the children to express their own interest by choosing their own materials. Materials that can be used in a variety of ways encourage children to solve problems creatively. The teacher’s responsibility is to create and maintain a physical setting that provides a balanced environment in which children’s strengths and interest are valued. Our preschoolers are supported as they learn to communicate and get along with others.

column1: Young Dimensions Childcare’s role is to expose children to learning
column2: not impose learning on them. Children have a natural love for learning. GRUBB ST";"COLUMBUS";"OH";43215;"FRANKLIN";6144619247;"http://www.homelessfamiliesfoundation.com/what-we-do/the-dowd-center/";" info@homelessfamiliesfoundation.org ";"Homeless children are the innocent victims in the tragedy of family homelessness.  Homelessness wounds children!  The core of the mission of The Homeless Families Foundation is to provide stability and nurturing to these at-risk children as they prepare to re-enter and remain independent within the greater community with their families.
Homeless children may be ill-prepared to start school
column2: and once in school
column3: may fall behind their peers academically.  The Dowd Education Center provides an academically focused afterschool and summer program which follows the curriculum of the Columbus City Schools and helps the children overcome their obstacles to success in school. We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.

column1: Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.

column6: a full hot lunch and an afternoon snack as well as weekly swimming lessons and weekly gymnastics classes. We strive to educate the parent about the importance of their role in their child’s education from the very beginning. We keep parents informed through newsletters

We also encourage the parents to participate in family events throughout the year and to utilize our facility. A strong family relationship is vital to the ongoing education of our children
column9: and we know that strong kids and strong families build strong communities.

This means that we believe knowledge is constructed rather than acquired through an active process of exploring
column2: investigating
column3: and playing. The curriculum
column4: which is inspired by the Reggio Emilia approach
column5: is built upon the notion that every child is capable and competent.

column1: Our approach is based on the following premises:
Children are full of potential
column2: have many ideas and theories
column3: and an eagerness to learn.

column1: Joyful learning is promoted daily.
Time spent outdoors is essential to a child's well-being.
Respect is accorded to all members of the community through encouraging and understanding multiple points of view.
The environment promotes interaction and cooperation.
Listening is a central role of the adult. Listening is reflected in the on-going documentation and study of children's ideas and investigations.
Communication is a reciprocal process involving the home and the school.
Parents are viewed as partners with teachers.

column3: LLC is a small Christian Preschool designed to help your child learn to work together with others and explore God's wonderful word as we prepare for life and learning.

column1: We'll have Bible stories and character building stories as well as many hands on activities to help your child discover the joys of learning.
Math and whole language can be fun
column2: even for little ones. We'll use many experiences of life to help us learn how things work as we explore reading
column3: writing
column4: art and math and music.

column1: Our classes will be small for a better learning experience for your child. Our teachers will have a college degree and have an assistant meeting the requirements of our license through ODJFS.
Students enjoy sharing with their friends and take turns bringing a snack for the group. We all have a lot of fun working and playing together.

You're welcome to visit our preschool and get acquainted with us. We have enrollment packs available to be returned with a $50 enrollment fee. We'll have you and your child come in for an interview and see how we can learn together.
We're a non-denominational Christian preschool that will encourage families to grow in their faith in Jesus as their Savior and Lord and attend a church that teaches God's Word.
Tutoring for students Pre K through Grade 6 can be arranged after school or on Friday afternoons. Check with us for more information.

column1: 991840;"MYCAP HEAD START CAMPBELL LEARNING CENTER";"2002 COMMUNITY CIRCLE";"CAMPBELL";"OH";44405;"MAHONING";3307996839;"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"mycapyoungstown@gmail.com";"The Mahoning Youngstown Community Action Partnership (MYCAP) was founded in 1965. We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.
Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People

991935;"ST. BONIFACE PRESCHOOL";"4305 PITTS AVENUE";"CINCINNATI";"OH";45223;"HAMILTON";5135022761;"http://stbonifaceschool.net/";"tconners@stbonifaceschool.net";"The roots of the current St. Boniface Parish church and school began with the building of a modest church on Delaney Street
column3: named St. Aloysius. Within the next few years
column4: due mainly to the steady influx of immigrants
column5: the parish had grown so large that the little church could no longer accommodate its parishioners. Rather than build a larger church
column6: then Archbishop Purcell
column7: favored the formation of second parish. On April 6
column9: the congregation unanimously resolved that a division be effected along ethnic lines: German and Irish. It was decided by the drawing of lots that the Irish would retain the original church property
column10: renaming the parish St. Patrick. The German community received the sum of $1500.00 to build a new church

column2: land was purchased at the corner of Blue Rock and Lakeman Streets and in November
column4: the new church was blessed. Students attended school in the parsonage and by 1867 it was decided that there was no longer adequate space at the parsonage to accommodate the steady increase in pupils. The parish purchased additional property adjacent to the church. By 1870
column5: an ornate
column6: solidly constructed
column7: two-story brick building consisting of four school rooms was erected on Blue Rock Street at a cost of $7

column2: however
column3: it was necessary to build an addition consisting of two rooms on the second floor as well as a chapel and meeting room on the ground floor. In the early 1900’s
column4: another large addition was made to the school and a residence was built on Lakeman Street for the Sisters of Charity who taught at the school. The parishes of St. Clare (College Hill) and St. Pius (South Cumminsville) branched off
column5: and still the parish and school grew. By 1913
column6: St. Boniface School had 600 pupils and in 1921
column7: the property at Chase and Pitts was purchased with plans for a new and much larger church.

column1: The present magnificent church and rectory were completed in 1927 and the existing school building opened in 1933. In 1979
column2: the parish school became a combined school with St. Boniface and St. Leo participating. At this time
column3: the governance of the school shifted from the parish to the newly formed St. Boniface School Board.

column1: The Sisters of Charity continued to serve the school until 1999.
Tina Conners is our current Principal.
Sister Ann Gorman
column2: a Sister of Mercy
column3: is our Administrative Assistant to the Principal.";"http://stbonifaceschool.net/";;;;;;"n";"n";"y";"y";"y";"y";"http://stbonifaceschool.net/files/school-logo-web.jpg";;;;;;

We are a non-profit Community Action Agency dedicated to helping families move from poverty and crisis to family stability and self-sufficiency.

column1: Community Action Agencies were formed by President Lyndon B. Johnson’s 1964 vision for a Great Society. There are 1
column2: 100 Community Action Agencies across the country and 50 in the State of Ohio. MYCAP is part of the National Community Action Partnership designated to serve residents in Mahoning County
column3: which encompasses the City of Youngstown
column4: suburban communities and the rural villages in the western part of the county.

column1: Today
column2: MYCAP provides critical programs and services. Some of these are Energy Assistance Programs
column3: which include home weatherization and utility payment assistance for eligible income homeowners; education and classroom instruction for individuals to increase the chances that they will secure employment; nutrition services for vulnerable mothers and young children; pre-school classes for young children so they are prepared and successful when they enter kindergarten; transportation for seniors and those with a disability in Western Mahoning County who need a ride to health providers
column4: grocery stores and other locations; and much more.

column1: We serve individuals and families who meet the federal poverty income guidelines. There are specific income guidelines for every program or service we provide. If you qualify
column2: please get in touch with us because we would love to help you.

column1: We have a federally mandated tripartite board composed of elected officials
column2: private sector representatives and low-income representatives committed to:

column1: Empowering low-income individuals and families in their effort to become self-sufficient.
Advocating for a poverty-free community.
Stimulating expansion of economic opportunity for the poor and the community through economic development programs and services.
MYCAP is Helping People
column2: Changing Lives.";"http://www.my-cap.org/locations";"https://www.facebook.com/pages/MYCAP-Mahoning-Youngstown-Community-Action-Partnership/253808185491";;"http://www.my-cap.org/about/employment";;;"n";"n";"y";"y";"n";"n";"http://www.my-cap.org/wp-content/themes/mycap/images/mycaplogo.png";;;;;;

column1: 1055846;"GATEWAY SCHOOL B.E.A.R. PROGRAM";"3602 INDIAN ROAD";"TOLEDO";"OH";43606;"LUCAS";"419-536-8329";"http://www.ohschools.k12.oh.us/districtNewsArticle.aspx?artID=757#sthash.CutEmwYB.dpbs";;"Ottawa Hills Local Schools will partner with Gateway School to offer an in-house program for kindergarten students during the half of the day that they are not scheduled for the kindergarten classroom. The development of the program is in response to the needs of many families for full-day programming for their kindergarten-age child.

The district sent a Request for Proposals to 21 area preschool and daycare providers to organize and implement a combination childcare/learning opportunities program at Ottawa Hills Elementary School. Of the proposals received
column2: the district has chosen to partner with Gateway School to provide the program. Gateway has titled their program “The B.E.A.R. Program” (Beyond Education and Recreation).

column1: The program will provide childcare
column2: but will also provide activities that support and reinforce the skills being taught in the kindergarten classroom. The program is not envisioned to be another half day of kindergarten
column3: but as a time for students to grow developmentally in a play-based environment that has opportunities for developmentally appropriate social interaction. The district will work closely with Gateway to offer long-term overviews and short-term information concerning units and lessons being covered in the kindergarten classroom so that B.E.A.R. Program activities will reinforce student learning.

column1: Gateway was chosen because of their teacher/student ratios (1:10)
column2: their experience in specializing in early childhood care
column3: their reasonable monthly fees
column4: and the qualifications of their teaching staff. Any staff member teaching in the B.E.A.R. Program will have an Associate’s or Bachelor’s Degree in Early Childhood Development. In addition
column5: the Program Director
column6: Dan O’Connor
column7: will be an integral part of leading and teaching the program.

column1: The program will be a separate entity
column2: organized and implemented within our elementary building. Gateway will be renting classroom space from the school district and will be using their expertise to partner with the district in providing a program that complements our district’s kindergarten program. - See more at: http://www.ohschools.k12.oh.us/districtNewsArticle.aspx?artID=757#sthash.CutEmwYB.a3IwoP8j.dpuf";"http://www.ohschools.k12.oh.us/districtNewsArticle.aspx?artID=757#sthash.CutEmwYB.dpbs";"https://www.facebook.com/pages/Ottawa-Hills-Local-Schools/378134162312781?hc_location=timeline";;"http://www.ohschools.k12.oh.us/AdministrativeDepartment2.aspx?aid=6";"http://www.ohschools.k12.oh.us/content_page2.aspx?cid=266";;"n";"n";"y";"y";"n";"n";;"http://www.ohschools.k12.oh.us/images/full/FlashHeader012-0.jpg";;;;;

1056238;"THE WORKSHOP LEARNING CENTER";"732 JACKSON STREET";"GREENVILLE";"OH";45331;"DARKE";"937-459-5937";"http://www.theworkshoplc.com/preschool-daycare/";;"Preschool Highlights:
Taught by a STATE Licensed Teacher
Standards based education
Theme driven curriculum
Focus on purposeful play
Caring & nurturing environment
Collaboration with local schools for  Kindergarten Readiness
Our part-time preschool will focus on the necessary skills for student success in Kindergarten and beyond.  A theme based
column2: standards driven curriculum taught by highly qualified and caring mentors will be the foundation of this program. Children ages 3-5 will be engaged in a variety of opportunities to play and explore the world around them in order to understand and foster the joy of learning.

column1: The staff at The Workshop Learning Center is well qualified. All of the teachers are currently licensed by the state of Ohio with classroom teaching experience. The director has over 10 years of experience teaching children.  Collaboration with local schools ensures that our program will prepare students for kindergarten.
Daily activities will vary and include language and math work
column2: music and movement
column3: arts and crafts
column4: fine motor development
column5: science exploration and dramatic play and much more.

column1: 1075637;"TREE OF KNOWLEDGE";"736 LAKEVIEW RD.";"CLEVELAND";"OH";44108;"CUYAHOGA";"216-299-6954";"http://www.treeofknowledge.us/";;"OUR MISSION is to aid academically at-risk
column2: or physically challenged children by providing psycho-educational services for them to achieve academic success leading to a productive and rewarding lifestyle.

column1: All too often
column2: children are taught in a “one size fits all” manner
column3: overlooking each child’s personal learning style. The reality is that we all learn in different ways. To be successful
column4: we all need to be taught and allowed to learn according to our own unique style. When a child’s uniquely effective learning style is discovered
column5: it works like magic. Suddenly
column6: the child actually enjoys learning and can awaken in him or herself an excitement to learn.

column1: The Tree of Knowledge is continuously building relationships with schools across the United States giving more students access to programming they need and deserve. At Tree of Knowledge Learning Centers
column2: our educational specialists access and reveal each child’s unique learning style and develop individualized educational plans that create an enthusiasm to learn.

column1: Our mission at Tree of Knowledge Learning Centers is to deliver psycho-educational services to children who are at-risk academically and/or physically so they can achieve academic success and develop hope for a rewarding life.";"http://www.treeofknowledge.us/";;;"http://www.treeofknowledge.us/contact/employment/";;;"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"not mentioned in the website";"http://www.treeofknowledge.us/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/ToK-logo-web1.png";"http://www.treeofknowledge.us/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/chalkboard.gif";"http://www.treeofknowledge.us/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/eager-schoolgirl-2.gif";;;;

column2: We Care...

column1: The needs of children and their parents are the primary concerns of Youthland Academy's child care philosophy. By providing the best possible daycare to children
column2: we are contributing to the happiness and the security of their parents and to the community they live in.

column1: First and foremost
column2: Youthland Academy provides children constant and alert supervision in a safe environment
column3: screened from hazards. The large classroom with designated area for learning centers provide for both quiet and active play. Our entire program is designed to enable children to have a positive self-concept and to know success and fulfillment through programs of positive self-concept and to know success from the beginning. This is possible because our Academy environment provides children the opportunity to be safe in their quest as natural leaders.

column1: Youthland Academy isn't merely a childcare center
column2: it's a ""learning center"" that assists children to realize success and fulfillment through programs of positive self-image. Children experience the joy of learning; they feel loved and accepted. Our program is our attitude.

column1: Our Teachers and Directors are provided monthly themes that ignite each child's unique pleasure in learning. The monthly curriculum suggests proven ways to include these themes in a variety of ""discovery centered"" activities. Using the curriculum's themes
column2: each teacher designs individualized lesson plans. We do not adhere to the standardized lesson plan because we feel there is no standard child or standard class. This is why we keep our teacher-child ratio at the level that comfortably supports personal attention.

column1: Included with classroom discovery and stimulation are field trips. At some of our Academies
column2: we also provide activities such as gymnastics and dance classes. These services enable parents to further enrich their children's lives without cutting into the quality time parents and children share after working hours.

column1: Progress reports are given to parents to keep them up-to-date on the total growth of their children. Formal conferences are scheduled yearly to discuss a child's progress. However
column2: parents are encouraged to meet their child's teacher and director
column3: and visit the Academy at any time they feel necessary.";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/locations/dayton";;" 6:30am to 6:30pm";;;;"y";"y";"y";"y";"y";"y";;"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/139/content_580490_10151499682281211_1585200262_n.jpg";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/7/content_nursery-school-teaching.jpg";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/138/content_1377348_10151877935546211_176283268_n.jpg";"http://www.youthlandacademy.com/uploads/ckeditor/pictures/3/content_preschool-classrooms.jpg";;
